The table next to us left while we were waiting, and their table got bussed. Some other folks across the way got served. A guy who worked there kept staring at us but that's about all the attention we got from the staff besides another worker who gave us the side eye while rushing over to take care of the people who sat down immediately behind us, basically before their bottoms hit the chairs. What Gazebo Cafe has going for it is an outdoor space with live music, but I'd classify the food and drinks as only "decent". This was our last meal in New Orleans and I'm glad I was able to fit in a shrimp poboy before leaving, but it honestly wasn't the best I've had, even considering the ones I've had outside of the state. The shrimp was fairly boring, the bread a bit chewy, and absolutely no sauce or anything that typically goes on it. With that being said, I asked for some sauce and made my own, added my own pickles, tomato, and lettuce and it wasn't bad. Great? No. Not bad? Sure. It came with fries, which were fine and I also ordered the gumbo. The gumbo was a little thin, but fine. Nice and hot (temperature-wise), which was appreciated on a somewhat chilly and windy day. I also ordered the top shelf Long Island ice tea, but for such a big drink, it wasn't very strong, although tasty. My vegetarian friend only had a few things to choose from, but ordered a salad, which turned out to be gigantic! Like, huge. And some cheese fries, which looked good. She also had a top shelf marg and said it was good. The band was super fun and the atmosphere, and super friendly seemed service, really brought this establishment to life!

This typical touristy French Quarter fast food establishment has the LARGEST chicken wings I have ever seen or eaten. Not completely sure they didn't come from a turkey - that's how big they are! The onion rings are okay. Indeed the food will satisfy a quick craving for relatively little money. The drinks are where I'd put my cash if I were you. Go to the walk-up window and order one of their ice cream daiquiris. They are so cold and delicious - sure to quench your desire for something chilled and alcoholy especially on any given hot and humid day in N'awlins! Personally, I like the Boomerang and the Banana ice cream daiquiris. Yes you can walk around the Quarter with your drink as long as it is not in a glass container and you are at least 21 years of age or older. Enjoy your time in the French Quarter y'all!
